'''William Ives''' (12 October 1943 – 31 August 2017)<ref>https://www.frankwarren.com/william-ives-12th-october-1943-31st-august-2017/</ref> was a British steel magnate who has been a major donor to the British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].<ref>[http://www.essexlifemag.co.uk/people/who_s_the_top_50_richest_in_essex_1_1641468 Who's the top 50 richest in Essex?] Philip Beresford, ''EssexLife'', 15 November 2010. Retrieved 2 October 2014.</ref><ref name=mirror/>

Ives was a former boxer who once worked as a doorman at [[Esmeralda's Barn]],<ref name=mirror>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/the-cameron-crony-and-the-kray-twins-tory-786608 The Cameron crony and the Kray twins: Tory donor admits working as gangsters' doorman.] James Lyons & David Collins, ''[[Daily Mirror|Mirror]]'', 11 April 2012. Retrieved 2 October 2014.</ref> the gambling club owned by the [[Kray Twins]] in the early 1960s. In 1973, he founded [[Rainham Steel]] which is the source of his wealth. In 2012, Ives accepted a [[Police caution|caution]] from [[Essex Police]] for harassing his ex-wife. The incident was seen in the British press as an embarrassment for the Conservative Party.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9194772/Tory-donor-cautioned-for-harassing-ex-wife.html Tory donor cautioned for harassing ex-wife.] ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'', 10 April 2012. Retrieved 2 October 2014.</ref>

